[3] Idaho (Canyon and Ada Counties)
Date: Fri 28 Mar 2014
Source: KTVB [edited]
http://www.ktvb.com/news/health/Whooping-cases-spike-in-Ada-and-Canyon-Counties-252999821.html


Ada County is seeing the highest number of cases of whooping cough in several years. Whooping cough can be potentially deadly to infants. "Right now, our numbers are about 4 times average, and they're continuing to grow," said Central District Health Staff Epidemiologist Sarah Correll. "We do realize that the number of cases we get reported to us is just a very small part of the actual cases in the community, so we're really just seeing the beginning." Correll suspects not everyone who has whooping cough is getting treated or is being tested for the disease. There are 26 confirmed cases so far in Canyon County and 25 in Ada County.

"It's not unusual to have a spike every 5 to 7 years, a little bit of whooping cough cycle, but what we do worry about is that the infants may be adversely affected because people aren't thinking whooping cough. And if an infant or a newborn baby is infected with whooping cough, that could be deadly," said Correll. Most of the cases they have seen in Ada County have been kids between 5 and 18 years old, and they usually see the disease transmitted within the household.

[Byline: Stephanie Zepelin]

