[4] Michigan (Antrim County)
Date:: Wed 26 Mar 2014
Source: Petroskey News [edited]
http://www.petoskeynews.com/charlevoix/news/local/whooping-cough-confirmed-in-antrim-county-child/article_0107468c-6919-5fc0-a7cc-8da68794c9af.html


Authorities recently confirmed pertussis, more commonly known as whooping cough, in an Antrim County student. The Health Department of Northwest Michigan mailed letters to parents in the affected school, to recommend students in that classroom be treated by their doctors with an antibiotic as a preventive measure. Letters also provided information about symptoms of the illness and vaccination recommendations.

According to the health department, the infected student did not receive an up-to-date pertussis vaccination.

"The best prevention is to ensure everyone in the family is vaccinated," said Joshua Meyerson, medical director for the Health Department of Northwest Michigan. "Make sure young children receive all 5 recommended doses of DTaP (diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis) vaccine at 2, 4, 6 and 15 months of age, and again between 4 and 6 years of age. Starting at age 11, everyone should receive at least one Tdap booster dose, even if they have had a regular tetanus (Td) vaccine recently. Routine hand-washing is also helpful."

Meyerson warns that those who refuse vaccination put others at risk. "Even if you aren't concerned about the threat of pertussis for yourself, you may be unknowingly spreading the illness to others, especially infants and young children, to whom it may be fatal," he said.

The health department offers all necessary immunizations, including Tdap and DTaP vaccines, through its clinics in Bellaire, Mancelona, Charlevoix, Gaylord and Harbor Springs/Petoskey.

[Byline: Rachel Brougham]

